    <section id="generating">
      <h2>The Generating Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">相生</span>)</h2>
      <p>Each element nourishes and gives rise to the next in a continuous cycle of creation &mdash; the "mother-child" relationship:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wood feeds Fire</strong> &mdash; wood burns to create flame</li>
        <li><strong>Fire creates Earth</strong> &mdash; fire produces ash, which becomes soil</li>
        <li><strong>Earth bears Metal</strong> &mdash; minerals and ores form within the earth</li>
        <li><strong>Metal collects Water</strong> &mdash; metal surfaces condense moisture</li>
        <li><strong>Water nourishes Wood</strong> &mdash; water is essential for plant growth</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="overcoming">
      <h2>The Overcoming Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">相克</span>)</h2>
      <p>Each element restrains and controls another, maintaining balance through regulation:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wood penetrates Earth</strong> &mdash; roots break through soil</li>
        <li><strong>Earth dams Water</strong> &mdash; levees contain floods</li>
        <li><strong>Water extinguishes Fire</strong> &mdash; water quenches flame</li>
        <li><strong>Fire melts Metal</strong> &mdash; the forge transforms ore</li>
        <li><strong>Metal chops Wood</strong> &mdash; the axe fells the tree</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Both cycles are essential. Without the generating cycle, nothing would grow. Without the overcoming cycle, growth would be unchecked. Together they model the dynamic equilibrium that governs all natural systems.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="medicine">
      <h2>Wu Xing in Chinese Medicine</h2>
      <p>The <em>Huangdi Neijing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">黃帝內經</span>, Yellow Emperor's Classic of Internal Medicine) maps the five elements to the body's organ systems (<span class="chinese-char">臟腑</span>), emotions, tastes, tissues, and sense organs. Wood governs the liver and gallbladder, associated with the emotion of anger and the taste of sour. Fire governs the heart and small intestine, associated with joy and bitterness. This framework has guided Chinese medical diagnosis and treatment for over two millennia.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="bazi-astrology">
      <h2>Wu Xing in BaZi and Astrology</h2>
      <p>In <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a>, the five elements are the fundamental building blocks of chart analysis. Each Heavenly Stem carries an element, and each Earthly Branch contains hidden elemental content. The balance (or imbalance) of elements in a person's birth chart determines their constitutional nature, strengths, and vulnerabilities. Combined with the <a href="/zodiac/">twelve zodiac animals</a>, the elements create the 60-year sexagenary cycle.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="fengshui">
      <h2>Wu Xing in Feng Shui</h2>
      <p>In <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a>, each direction carries an elemental association: North is Water, South is Fire, East is Wood, West is Metal, Centre is Earth. Practitioners use these correspondences to assess whether a space's elemental composition supports its occupants. Materials, colours, and shapes all carry elemental qualities that can be adjusted to create harmony.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="governance">
      <h2>Wu Xing in Governance and History</h2>
      <p>Zou Yan proposed that dynastic succession followed the overcoming cycle: each dynasty was associated with an element, and its successor represented the conquering element. The Qin Dynasty claimed Water (overcoming the Zhou's Fire). The Han Dynasty claimed Earth (overcoming Qin's Water), later revised to Fire. This theory intertwined with the Mandate of Heaven (<span class="chinese-char">天命</span>), providing a cosmological framework for political legitimacy.</p>
    </section>
